How to Win in DOTA 2 If You're a Data Scientist
¶

Brian Chin, Allison Wei, Dan Zou
¶

Background¶

Dota 2 is a multiplayer online battle arena (MOBA) game developed and published by Valve. The game is a sequel to Defense of the Ancients (DotA), and is played in matches between two teams of five players (5 vs. 5), with each team occupying and defending their own separate base on the map. Each of the ten players independently controls a powerful character, known as a "hero", who all have unique abilities and differing styles of play (only one of each hero in each match). During a match, players collect experience points and items for their heroes to successfully defeat the opposing team's heroes in player versus player combat. A team wins by being the first to destroy the other team's "Ancient", a large structure located within their base. More info here.

We are looking at a dataset pulled through using da-steve101's Dota 2 api loader found here. The dataset (hosted on UCI's ML repository) are of games which were played in a span of 2 hours on the August 13th, 2016. This data contains the result of which team has lost and which team has won, the regions, the game types, the heros that were chosen.

In this tutorial, our mission is to tidy the data, and provide insight onto which 5 heros are the most successful in terms of the win rate, and which hero choices will result in the highest win rate in each game (similar to what was done in this UC San Diego study. In this game, each hero (111 total) have different skills and roles which would allow for very different combinations of teams. With our analysis we hope to find our if it is possible to find teams that are more successful than others, and have a higher probability of winning. For readers that are unfamiliar, or are just getting into the game, we hope that our analysis will either make them more interested in Dota 2, or help provide some information on which heros to pick in certain lineups. For people who have more experience in the game, this may help them choose better heros for the meta (most effective tactics available).

Importing and Preparation¶

We'll be using multiple different libraries to process and display our data. We'll be using urllib and requests to access data from the internet. Processing will occur with pandas, numpy, statsmodel, and sklearn. Finally, visualizations will be performed by matplotlib, seaborn, and yellowbrick (more on yellowbrick later).

It's also pre split into a training set and a testing set. The data is stored as a zip on UCI's servers, so we'll use the zipfile library to extract the files from it.

The training data contains more than 90,000 observations, with the testing data containing over 10,000. This is plenty for what we're doing, and we'll in fact be filtering out a significant portion of it later.

Before continuing, we'll have to prepare the datasets. As it stands, the dataset has no column names, and all of the categorical data uses magic numbers instead of their actual names. We'll apply the same transformations to both datasets as we'll have to verify our results on the testing dataframe later.

In the data, the first row is for which team won (so in effect we have two times the data, because we can extract which 5 set of heros resulted in a loss, and which resulted in a win), with 1 being Radiant winning, and -1 for Dire winning. The next column (column 1) is the region of the world that the game data occured, and the following two rows are the game types that were played from All Pick to Greeviling (More explination here or here). From column 4 onwards to 116, are the different heros as listed in this database. Note that number 24 is missing for unknown reasons (there is no data in that row as well as no hero existing for that number either). Furthermore, the hero Abyssal Underlord was not patched in at this time, so no data exists either for that id (108). The keys for all this data was found here under "lobbies," "mods," and "heroes."

Heroes:¶

Data on the magic numbers can be found at kronusme/dota2-api. We can then extract the mapping from each JSON file to produce a dictionary of replacements to later be given to replace.

We will also drop two columns, the column associated with ID 24 and the column associated Abyssal Underlord. As explained above, for unexplained reasons, Valve never assigned a hero to ID 24. Nevertheless, due to how the data was generated, a 24th hero column exists, but is simply populated with zeroes. We will also drop the column associated with Abyssal Underlord. At the time of the data's generation, Abyssal Underlord was an unreleased hero, but a column for him for exists in the dataset anyway as his ID is smaller than the IDs of heroes that had already been released. As such, the column associated with Abyssal Underlord is also filled with zeroes.

Preliminary Investigation¶

Win Rates By Hero¶

One natural question is, do certain heroes win more often than others? We can easily extract the win rates for each hero by summing the number of times they win and dividing by the number of matches they're in.

In [13]:
win_loss_count = train_df.groupby('Win/Lose').sum().iloc[:, -len(heroes_list):]
totals = win_loss_count.sum()
win_proportion = (win_loss_count.iloc[1] / totals).sort_values()
win_proportion

Wow! Our r-squared is only 0.07. It looks like there isn't a strong relationship between the selection frequency and the win-rate after all. One reason this might be is that heroes with higher win rates are simply harder to play and require more skill, making them less likely to be chosen. However, when chosen, they do very well. In the middle of our plot, we see the heroes that are most frequently chosen, likely because they're easier to master, and thus the playing ground is roughly level among all the people who select the hero, leading to about a 50% win rate.

The southeast Asia region absolutely dominates the other regions in number of games played. It's important to note however that the data was collected over a two time span on a single day. It's not mentioned what time of day that is, so the signficant bias towards Souteast Asia could simply be due to when the data was collected and not completely because of the game's popularity in Asia.

We will work with proportions instead of absolute counts, so for the sake of simplicity, we will assume that the two hours of gameplay data is representative of gameplay behavior overall, aside from absolute regional distribution characteristics like games played.

One trend we may be interested in is whether certain characters are selected more frequently than others. We can investigate this trend by first finding the proportion of times each hero is selected. We then find the standard deviation of the relative selection frequencies for each hero with respect to the regions. Larger standard deviations suggest that that character's selection frequency is more varied.

It looks like the least varied hero selection frequencies is simply due to them not being selected at all; their selection frequency is very close to zero.

The hero with the largest selection frequency variation is Phantom Assassin. It looks like the character is heavily preferred in South Korea, Southeast Asia, and India with nearly 5% of matches containing Phantom Assassin. Interestingly, in China, it's less preferred. When examining some other heroes like Huskar and Riki, we see that their high variance is caused by South Africa strongly preferring not to use the hero, with close to 0% of matches containing Huskar and Riki there.

A misleading aspect here is that some characters are simply less popular than others. If a character is less popular, then the standard deviation will be smaller. We can try to compensate for this by scaling the data so that the frequency mean is all the same, and then remeasuring variance.

Hero Pairs¶

Suppose you're playing DOTA 2 with a friend, and you want to know which pair of heroes will maximize the probability that you two will win. Instead of selecting a single hero, we now have to select two.

To perform this analysis, first all pairs of heroes were generated. For each pair, we then found their win proportion by dividing the win count by the number of rows in which a team contained both heroes.

In [28]:
hero_pairs = [(h1, h2) for h1, h2 in itertools.combinations(heroes_list, 2)]
In [29]:
rates = []
for h1, h2 in hero_pairs:
    filtered = train_df[['Win/Lose', h1, h2]][(train_df[h1] == 1) & (train_df[h2] == 1)]
    f_totals = filtered.sum()
    # calculate win rate and add to list
    rates.append(f_totals['Win/Lose'] / len(filtered) if len(filtered) != 0 else 0)

# construct dataframe from pairs and win rates
paired_win_rates = pd.DataFrame({'Hero1': [h1 for h1, _ in hero_pairs], 'Hero2': [h2 for _, h2 in hero_pairs], 'Rates': rates})

Now that the paired win rates are in a dataframe, we can again use a heatmap to examine which pairs have higher win rates. To do this, we'll first have to pivot the dataframe so that it's 111 by 111 instead of the current 111^2 by 1. Doing so allows the heatmap to directly map dataframe values into the heatmap.

In [30]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,8))

ax.set_xlabel("Hero")

Interesting! It looks like there are indeed some pairs that stand out in terms of their win rate. It's also interesting to note the pairs that have a zero percent win rate. These may simply be because the pairs don't show up however, like along the diagonal. Some heroes are better paired than others, so it makes sense that certain pairs may never appear in more competitive gameplay.

Predicting Game Outcome¶

We saw earlier that certain characters had much higher win rates than others. Given a match up two teams of five, can we possibly determine whether the team will win or not?

To do this, we will first take our training and testing dataframes and extract our input elements and output values out. Our input elements will be the indicator columns for all the heros with the outputs the Win/Loss column

In [38]:
heros_train = train_df.drop(columns[:-len(heroes_list)], axis=1)
heros_test = test_df.drop(columns[:-len(heroes_list)], axis=1)

X_train = heros_train.values
X_test = heros_test.values

y_train = list(train_df['Win/Lose'])
y_test = list(test_df['Win/Lose'])

We tried multiple different models and hyper parameters, but our results across all of them were relatively similar. Generally, our score, that is how well we were able to predict the game outcome, was about 0.56. While hero choice may have some bearing on game outcome, it really does come down to skill. We looked at the models: logistic regression, SVM, MLP Classifier (using adam, sgd, lbfgs).

Of the above methods that we looked at, we'll examine logistic regression more closely since its score was the highest among the others. How did logistic regression perform over time? The yellowbrick library allows us to examine training and cross validation score over time. We specify a 5-fold cross validation.

In [44]:
model = LogisticRegression(random_state=0, solver='lbfgs', multi_class='ovr').fit(X_train, y_train)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
visualizer = LearningCurve(model, cv=5, ax=ax)
visualizer.fit(X_train, y_train)
ax.set_ylabel('Score')
ax.set_xlabel('Training Instances')
ax.set_title("Learning Curve Logistic Regression; solver LBFGS")
ax.legend()
fig.show()

From the learning curve, we see that convergence occurs around 40000 training instances. The training and test scores are relatively close by 60000 instances, so more test data may not help with better convergence. Variance in the cross validation score suggests that some overfitting is occuring.

Conclusions¶

We saw at the beginning that there were some interesting trends in the dataset we were examining. Indeed, some heroes and hero pairs had higher win percentages and some regions preferred certain heroes over others. However, a team is composed of more than merely its parts (what a cliche). Given that a hero may only appear once per team and that the game is primarily skill based, predicting game outcomes was unsuccessful. We did not do much better than simply guessing.

One limitation with this dataset was that we only had data on the heroes present in each match up. There's no data on player skill, experience, or any other statistics. Given such data, while the problem dimensionality would increase, it would be significantly more likely that we could find a relationship between certain heroes or skill statistics.
